The correct way to do this is to use the [File System](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v8.x/docs/api/fs.html) module.

```js
var fs = require('fs')
var JSON5 = require('json5')

// Get the JSON5 file as a string
var json5Text = fs.readFileSync('./file.json5')

// Parse the JSON5 text
var value = JSON5.parse(json5Text)

// Convert the value to JSON
var jsonText = JSON.stringify(value)
```

As a one-liner, this could be:

```js
JSON.stringify(
    require('json5').parse(
        require('fs').readFileSync('./file.json5')
    )
)
```

---

The reason your code won't work is because `require` attempts to parse JSON5 files as JavaScript, which will either result in a parsing error or will will return an empty object because JSON5 files do not contain any [`export` statements](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v8.x/docs/api/modules.html#modules_module_exports).

However, you can make `require` parse JSON5 files by using the following code as [documented in the README](https://github.com/json5/json5#nodejs-require-json5-files).

```js
// Make require parse JSON5 files
require('json5/lib/register')

// Require and parse a JSON5 file
var value = require('./file.json5')

// Convert the value to JSON
var jsonText = JSON.stringify(value)
```

@octogonz I did most of the work on the jsonc-parser. The syntax (json + comments) had been around for quite some years already , e.g in Sublime configuration files, that's why we picked it.
We always thought of it as VSCode internal thing and never had ambitions of making it a new standard.
Also, recently, it has lost importance in VSCode as we've added a settings UI. I'm also a fan of keeping syntaxes simple and well-defined and like the approach json5 has taken. Let's not add another flavor of JSON. I'm not aware of many requests to make the VSCode configuration file syntax richer, but if there were, we'd probably go with JSON5 as the format of our configuration files.
